          <TD WIDTH="100%"><A NAME="186"></A>
          <FONT FACE="verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif" SIZE=2> <B>Blast from the Past</B> (<A HREF="/comments/2004/3/9/16838/14935/186?mode=alone;showrate=1#186">none / 0</A>) (<A CLASS="light" HREF="/comments/2004/3/9/16838/14935/186#186">#186</A>)  </FONT> <BR>
          <FONT FACE="verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif" SIZE=2>by <A HREF="/user/uid:6348">Waldo</a> on Sun Mar 21, 2004 at 02:17:43 AM EST<BR> </FONT>
          </TD>
        </TR>
      </TABLE>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
  <TR>
    <TD>
    <FONT FACE="verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif" SIZE=2> screen was the way to go back when SLIP was the preferred method of connecting to the Internet, the WWW was just some thing Tim BL was playing with at CERN, and command-line access was the only way to fly. &nbsp;I could initiate a zmodem transfer to transfer a file onto my home computer while downloading a file through FTP to my shell account and also running a search in WAIS. &nbsp;It was totally cool.<p>
But...uh...that was 1992. &nbsp;Now, I have a GUI. &nbsp;No screen for me.<p>
-Waldo Jaquith <BR><BR> </FONT>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<UL><LI><FONT FACE="verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif" SIZE=2> <a class="light" href="/comments/2004/3/9/16838/14935?pid=186#188">multiplexing</a> by Torako, </FONT><FONT FACE="arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif" SIZE=2>03/21/2004 07:31:14 AM EST (<b>none / 0</b>)</FONT></LI></UL>

